SIMPLE: disavow
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Disavow
<hw>Dis`a*vow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Disavowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Disavowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧savouer</ets>; pref. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧s-</ets> (L.
<ets>dis</ets>-) + <ets>avouer</ets> to avow. See <er>Avow</er>, and cf.
<er>Disavouch</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To refuse strongly and
solemnly to own or acknowledge; to deny responsibility for, approbation
of, and the like; to disclaim; to disown; <as>as, he was charged with
embezzlement, but he <ex>disavows</ex> the crime</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A solemn promise made and <qex>disavowed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deny; to show the contrary of; to
disprove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet can they never⟦br⟧
Toss into air the freedom of my birth,⟦br⟧
Or <qex>disavow</qex> my blood Plantagenet's.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>disavowable</ent>⟦br⟧
